subSubSection.paragraph:
Description. Male.
Body length 
7.7–13.8 mm
, humeral width 1.3–2.0 mm. Body mostly yellowish-brown, with brown setae and golden pubescence. Head dark brown; mandible black apically; frons brown (
Fig. 1e
). Antennae fringed with sparse brown setae on inner sides of basal six antennomeres, covered with shorter silvery golden pubescence on external sides (
Fig. 1b
). Pronotum covered with silvery golden pubescence, forming some markings due to the different direction of the pubescence (
Fig. 1d
). Elytra with sparse golden brown setae..

Head slightly narrower than pronotum (
Figs. 1d
, 
11
); frons short, subrectangular, with a longitudinal median sulcus (
Fig. 1e
); eye large, upper eye lobes very close to each other (
Figs. 1d, 1e
), with lower eye lobes narrower towards middle (
Fig. 1e
). Antennae slightly longer than body, surpassing elytral apices by two antennomeres, antennomere III slightly shorter than antennomere IV, antennomere V the longest, antennomeres V–XI gradually decreasing in length. Pronotum much longer than broad, ratio of length to width ca. 1.5; discal middle region forming a marking by the special directions of pubescence, with a curved ridge surrounding the middle region (
Figs. 1d
, 
11
), which appearing a “u” shaped median notch near the pronotal apical margin. Scutellum ligulate. Elytra subparallel-sided, length about 4 to 5 times as long as humeral width; humeri rounded, slightly protruding forward; apices rounded; disc finely punctate, with a seta from each puncture. Prosternum covered with grayish pubescence except apical area (
Figs. 1c
, 
12
). Mesoventrite transverse. Metaventrite longer than wide, with a longitudinal median indentation at posterior half. Pro- and mesoventral processes very short (
Fig. 12
). Abdomen cylindrical, distinctly narrower than thorax, first ventrite longer than others (
Fig. 1c
). Legs short, femora strongly widened except basal stalk, laterally flattened; hind femora exceeding second ventrite; metatarsomere I nearly twice as long as two next combined, claws divaricate.

Male terminalia
(
Figs. 3–7
). Tegmen (
Fig. 6
) about 
1.1 mm
in length, strongly curved near middle and apical half in lateral view (
Fig. 6b
); lateral lobes strongly reduced, only visible as a wide and shallow groove at apical part of tegmen (
Figs. 6a, 6c
). Median lobe with median struts slightly curved (
Fig. 4a
), much longer than tegmen; median struts about 3/5 of whole length of median lobe (
Figs. 7a, 7b
); ventral plate pointed at apex (
Fig. 7a
); median foramen elongate; internal sac with two sclerites at base (
Figs. 4c, 7a, 7c
) and a long apical region with many tiny sclerites (
Fig. 5
). Tergite VIII (
Fig. 3c
) trapezoidal, truncate on apex with rounded angles, slightly protruding, provided with semi-long setae along sides. Sternite VIII (
Fig. 3a
) well developed, with two protruding apical lobes like ears of cat at sides, with slightly shorter setae (compared with setae on tergite VIII).
